Take a moment to watch this. It’s so moving, so emotional. Anyone who has lost someone understands the plea of this song. We all long for someone to look at us, to see us, to accept us, as is.

@mattmauserofficial sings to his wife, who he lost in the helicopter crash that took Kobe Bryant and 8 others, in this stirring performance on @agt. Life goes on, but it’s never the same. We are all standing here asking for similar things. Tread gently today. #movehumanityforward

node.text:
If you’ve gotten on a plane lately or are planning a trip this summer, this is definitely a conversation you need to listen to! I wanted to speak with Sara Nelson, the International President of the 
Association of Flight Attendants-CWA to get her take on what is really happening in the air and how we can get back to traveling safely. Sara made so many great points, but most of all that flight attendants are there first and foremost to keep us safe, not to serve us. As we travel this summer, and especially over the busy 4th of July holiday, let’s remember that this is a stressful time. Let’s be grateful, be thankful, and kind. Let’s listen to the rules, because they are designed to keep all of us safe. Thank you for joining me, Sara! Travel safe everyone! Where (and are you) traveling this summer? Let me know in the comments below! ✈️ #wevebeenthinking

node.text: Nearly one billion women worldwide will go through menopause by the year 2025, yet many doctors aren’t trained in this stage of life. I was honored to join my colleagues on @3rdhourtoday this morning to help break down the stigmas surrounding menopause and help more women understand the myths associated with menopause. Thank you to @thewoolfer and @drjengunter for joining me to share your stories and make talking about menopause less taboo! #womenshealthmatters

node.text: Today marks the first federal celebration of Juneteenth. Juneteenth is about so much more than just the end of slavery. It’s about hope, it’s about the fight for freedom, it’s about the belief that this country can be better. As we learn more about this holiday and understand why we celebrate, let’s see this as just one step forward in acknowledging our history and as a way of moving humanity forward. Happy Juneteenth! #juneteenth

node.text: I loved getting to catch up with my @todayshow colleague, Craig Melvin and chat all about his new book, “Pops: Learning to Be a Son and a Father.” This is the perfect book to celebrate Father’s Day, and it was special hearing from Craig why and how he chose to write this book. Craig’s father struggled with addiction, and the process of writing this book not only helped Pop’s unburden his mistakes and errors from the past, but it helped Craig unburden himself and become a better father. To watch the full conversation AND to read an excerpt from this wonderful book, make sure to subscribe to @thesundaypaper in the link in my bio! #wevebeenthinking

node.text:
What a great conversation with mom, fitness guru, @thetalkcbs host, and now author, Amanda Kloots! Amanda released her book, “Live Your Life” Tuesday, written with sister, @annakloots. The book is a beautiful and heartbreaking account of her husband, Nick’s fight with and ultimate death due to COVID.

As we come upon Amanda’s first Father’s Day without Nick, it was beautiful hearing how her brother and father have stepped up and into her son, Elvis’s life to help father him. I also loved Amanda’s reminder that family is not just those who share the same blood, but those we choose (and who choose us). To listen to the full conversation, make sure to subscribe to @thesundaypaper in the link in my bio, and also tune in on my Instagram today as I talk more about fatherhood with my friend, @craigmelvinnbc! #wevebeenthinking

node.text: Thank you, Christiane for not only spreading awareness of Ovarian Cancer, but using your platform to encourage every woman to listen to their body. Only you can know when something doesn’t feel right, when something feels off. Take this moment to check in with yourself, check in with your health, and make time whether, daily, weekly, or monthly, to keep checking in. Advocate for your health, and speak up when you know something is wrong. Prevention and early intervention is key, but we can’t depend solely on a yearly doctor’s appointment. We must also do the work for ourselves. We must be the informed advocate for ourselves and those we love! #inspireheartsandminds

node.text:
Today is International Friendship Day and Sunday is National Friendship Day, so it got me thinking about friends. This past year has been a difficult one for friendships, but in many ways it has made me appreciate my friends more. It has made me appreciate the smaller gestures, the simple check ins, the little texts saying “How are you?” I think it has also made me a better friend, and made me realize what I need and want in my friends.

I share this picture of these chairs on this Friendship Day with you to ask yourself, who do you want sitting in these chairs with you? Who makes you feel great, makes you feel alive, and brings you joy? Who, even if you haven’t physically seen them in a year or more, do you wish was sitting across from you right now? Think about this. And then tag them below, reach out to them, and thank them here or elsewhere for being your friend! #internationalfriendshipday

node.text:
In this past week’s edition of @thesundaypaper, I wrote about betting on myself. For so long, I tried to make an idea I had into a reality by convincing others to bet on me. I got one “no" after another. Yes, I did. I tried to convince others to fund a brain wellness company that could nourish, educate, and empower people my age and in other generations to live a brain-healthy lifestyle. Finally, I decided to bet on myself (along with @patrickschwarzenegger), and the company launches in the fall! You can head up to my stories or link in bio to learn more about @moshlife.

So I want to know, when was the last time you bet on yourself? When was the last time you defied the odds and trusted your gut? Let me know in the comments below! And to read more from The Sunday Paper, head up to my link in bio and subscribe now! #ivebeenthinking

When it comes to @simonebiles, can we all just pause a moment and take a beat. This is a decorated Olympic athlete, who has endure more pressure and expectations than almost anyone.

If she needs a day, so be it. If she needs more than a day, so be it. Let’s not loose focus on all the other athletes breaking records and making us proud, and give her the time and space she needs! #tokyoolympics

node.text:
These fearless four testified today, and I for one was blown away by their honesty, their heroism, and their sense of duty. They told their stories of trying to defend our capital and everyone it in it. They spoke about defending our democracy — for all of us. They spoke about the mob of terrorists, who tried to take them out. We all owe Sgt. Aquilino Gonell, officer Michael Fanone, officer Daniel Hodges, officer Harry Dunn, and so many more our deepest gratitude, and  we owe it to them to do something about what happened to them.

I was also deeply moved by several political leaders who were also clearly deeply moved today. There is only one narrative here — the capital was attacked. America was attacked. A mob descended into our house, spurred on by someone who couldn’t accept a loss, someone who couldn’t accept the truth. This isn’t about politics. This is about us as a country. What we will accept, what we will deny. January 6th happened. Let’s hold those responsible for what happened. The truth is these officers put their lives on the line for us. What are we going to do to show them we believe them and we care? #abovethenoise

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Maria Shriver on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Appreciate where you are in your journey Even if it's not where you want be. Every season serves a purpose. to @mariashriver'.

node.text:
Take time to appreciate your journey today. Not every moment will be wonderful, not every moment will feel great, but those are the moments that make you who you are. Those are the moments that you look back on, knowing you succeeded and made it through. Those are the moments that make you the person you want to be.

Head out onto your journey today, wherever you are on your path. Appreciate the moments, because it is all for a purpose! Tag a friend in the comments that needs this reminder today. 🏷 #inspiredaging

node.text: Dwell in the possibility of your own possibility. Trust in new beginnings. Trust that your best days are indeed yet to be lived. Bet on yourself. For even more inspiration, make sure you subscribe to @thesundaypaper in my link in bio. #mondaymeditation
